  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing User Intent**\n\nI\'m deep in the weeds, analyzing the user\'s request. My focus is on determining the exact scope of the React application build, based on the UI design mockups and instructions provided. I\'m assessing the complexity and deliverables, specifically from the perspective of an elite full-stack engineer and UI lead. I want to build a truly robust and delightful application.\n\n\n**Defining Scope and Features**\n\nI\'ve got a much clearer picture now. I\'m focusing on the critical development requirements, particularly the \"Vibrant Aurora Glassmorphism\" aesthetic and the need for a deep dark background stretched across the screen. I\'m also considering the password-protected modules, specifically \"Study,\" \"Expense,\" and \"Diet.\" My focus is on delivering a pixel-perfect replication, with a focus on interactivity, clean code, and a smooth user experience.\n\n\n**Clarifying App Structure**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the application\'s module architecture and login flow. I\'m prioritizing the main `App.tsx` component to manage state, specifically `isAuthenticated`. Considering the user\'s explicit requirement for password protection of \"Study,\" \"Expense,\" and \"Diet\" modules, I\'m leaning toward a global lock screen. I\'m building an initial login screen. The non-password-protected modules (Skills, Tasks, etc.) will be directly accessible.\n\n\n**Refining Access Control**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing the password-protected module approach, and I\'ve decided to implement a PIN-based lock screen for the \"Study,\" \"Expense,\" and \"Diet\" modules individually, instead of a global login. The login screen might be optional but more performant as a global screen, with a main screen at the root for `!isAuthenticated`. I\'m focused on flexibility with 8 modules, with 3 locked.\n\n\\n\\n\n\n**Prioritizing Implementation**\n\nI\'m starting with a type definition file, and then the core application layout and sidebar, considering Tailwind CSS v4 and Framer Motion integration. I\'ll utilize `lucide-react` for icons to ensure consistency within the chosen tech stack. I\'m focusing on perfectly matching the visual design.\n\n\n**Structuring Module Interactions**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing the routing and state management for active modules, focusing on the navigation sidebar (`src/components/Sidebar.tsx`). Custom colors are now going into `index.css`, as per the Tailwind config. I\'m building out the `TopBar.tsx` for search and notifications, and the module list, including the PIN lock component, and background elements. I\'m focusing on `index.css` for Tailwind v4 configuration, using CSS variables and `@theme`, or standard utility classes, extending colors as needed.\n\n\n**Implementing Tailwind Config**\n\nI\'ve added the provided custom color definitions to `index.css` using CSS variables within a `@theme` block, ready for Tailwind configuration. I\'m focusing on defining these colors to align with the visual design.\n\n\n**Defining Color Configuration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on implementing the custom colors in Tailwind CSS, integrating the design system into the app, and I\'ve established a solid foundation for the visual design. I am also working through the provided custom color definitions for the vibrant ledger components. I\'ve begun to define these colors.\n\n\n**Defining Typography**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing the typographical scale for this design, and I\'m focused on extracting the font and text sizes to use CSS variables for global consistency. I\'m building out the type scale, which includes fonts, spacing, and weights for mobile and desktop for different headings and body text.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 19
      nanos: 128083681
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
